    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/gene-length-offset-matrix-computation/008",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": null,
      "asbval:note": "The paper does not mention a specific function 'DESeqDataSetFromTximport' or describe automatic offset embedding. The paper states that tximport exports 'offsets that can be used as inputs to common statistical engines, such as DESeq2' but does not detail a specific DESeq2 function that automatically constructs or embeds offsets from tximport output. This is a claim about implementation detail not present in the passages.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-12688-f1000research-7563-1",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "no",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "gene-length-offset-matrix-computation",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools[DESeq2].role",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "DESeqDataSetFromTximport function accepts tximport output and automatically constructs and embeds the offset matrix into the DESeqDataSet for use in differential expression analysis",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0007675"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T19:12:50.801566+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000340"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/gene-length-offset-matrix-computation/009",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "we provide an R package, tximport, to import transcript lengths and abundance estimates from several popular quantification packages and export (estimated) count matrices and, optionally, average transcript length correction terms (i.e., offsets) that can be used as inputs to common statistical engines... Accounting for the potentially varying average transcript length across samples when performing DGE, either in the definition of the count matrix (scaledTPM) or by defining offsets, led to considerably improved false discovery rate (FDR) control... this improvement is entirely attributable to an improved handling of genes with changes in isoform composition between the conditions",
      "asbval:note": "Semantic equivalence: paper describes tximport as accepting transcript-level quantification and producing offsets to handle differential isoform usage (DTU).",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-12688-f1000research-7563-1",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "gene-length-offset-matrix-computation",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "You have transcript-level quantification (salmon, Sailfish, or kallisto output) summarized to gene level by tximport, and you observe or suspect differential isoform usage across your experimental conditions.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T19:12:50.801566+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/gene-length-offset-matrix-computation/010",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "Several different quantification approaches have been proposed, ranging from simple counting of reads that overlap given genomic regions to more complex estimation of underlying transcript abundances... Several software packages have been developed for performing such 'simple' counting (e.g., feature Counts and HTSeq-count). More recently, the field has seen a surge in methods aimed at quantifying the abundances of individual transcripts (e.g., Cufflinks, RSEM, Bit Seq, kallisto and Salmon).",
      "asbval:note": "Semantic equivalence: paper distinguishes between simple counting methods (featureCounts, HTSeq) and transcript-level quantification methods (Salmon, kallisto), implying the latter provide transcript-level information needed for offset construction.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-12688-f1000research-7563-1",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "gene-length-offset-matrix-computation",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Input counts are from alignment-based methods (e.g., HTSeq, featureCounts) rather than pseudo-alignment (salmon/kallisto); these do not provide transcript-length estimates needed for offset construction.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T19:12:50.801566+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/gene-level-summarization-from-transcripts/000",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "we provide an R package ( tximport) to help users integrate transcript-level abundance estimates from common quantification pipelines into count-based statistical inference engines. ... taking advantage of transcript-level abundance estimates when defining or analyzing gene-level abundances leads to improved differential gene expression results compared to simple counting.",
      "asbval:note": "Core claim is directly supported by abstract and introduction.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-12688-f1000research-7563-1",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "gene-level-summarization-from-transcripts",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Aggregate transcript-level abundance, counts, and length estimates into gene-level matrices using a transcript-to-gene mapping. This approach corrects for differential isoform usage across samples and enables gene-level differential expression analysis with improved statistical p",
